<paragraph id="8BCA36E73370447FEBC2FEA8FD268597" blockId="3.[151,1436,258,463]" pageId="3">
This species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D643370447FEA8EFEAEFDB68543" box="[475,542,260,283]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Homotropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis id="B901EAF53370447FEA8EFEAEFDB68543" box="[475,542,260,283]" italics="true" pageId="3">pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (according to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B163370447FE83AFEA8FBA78543" author="Dasch" box="[879,1039,258,283]" pageId="3" refString="Dasch, C. E. (1964 a) Ichneumon-flies of America north of Mexico 5: Subfamily Diplazontinae. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 3, 1 - 304." type="journal article" year="1964" yearSuffix="a">
Dasch, 
<number id="3DBD24C03370447FE893FEA8FBAA8543" box="[966,1026,258,283]" pageId="3" value="1964.0">1964</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
). Its black coxae and large size in combination with a strongly coriaceous and matt mesosoma distinguish it from most species there-in. In terms of size, it could be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D643370447FEAA6FEE6FCF6853B" authority="Thomson" authorityName="Thomson" box="[499,862,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Homotropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megaspis">
<emphasis id="B901EAF53370447FEAA6FEE6FD45853B" box="[499,749,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="3">Homotropus megaspis</emphasis>
Thomson
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D643370447FE8C1FEE6FBD9853B" authority="Uchida" authorityName="Uchida" box="[916,1137,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Homotropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="momoi">
<emphasis id="B901EAF53370447FE8C1FEE6FBAB853B" box="[916,1027,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="3">H. momoi</emphasis>
(Uchida)
</taxonomicName>
; from the former, it differs by the dark coxae, and from both by the coriaceous sculpture of the mesosoma. The otherwise similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D643370447FEE44FEC5FECF85F3" authority="Uchida" authorityName="Uchida" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Homotropus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areolaris">
<emphasis id="B901EAF53370447FEE44FEC5FF5585F3" italics="true" pageId="3">Homotropus areolaris</emphasis>
(Uchida)
</taxonomicName>
differs by the coloration of the stigma in the fore wing, the coloration of the fore and mid coxae, and the more extensive coriaceous sculpture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF0A666F3370447FEBC2FBB2FB0E8075" box="[151,1190,1048,1070]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230799/files/figure.png" pageId="3" targetBox="[151,1435,515,1026]" targetPageId="3">
